ard Mathematics","start_year":1927,"end_year":1940}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"He taught a future president at Groton","body":"Before joining Harvard, Coolidge taught at Groton, where one of his pupils was Franklin Delano Roosevelt; the two remained friends for life. He went on to spend his whole career at Harvard, chairing its mathematics department."},{"number":2,"category":"science","header":"He held Oxford’s first science degree","body":"After Harvard, Coolidge took the very first Bachelor of Science ever awarded by Oxford, in 1897, then a doctorate at Bonn under Eduard Study. His treatises on the circle, the sphere, and non-Euclidean geometry became standards."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"He built Lowell House from raw brick","body":"Named the first master of Lowell House in 1930, Coolidge had to invent the residential culture of a building “new and raw from the builders’ hands.” His vision shaped Harvard’s house system for generations."},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"A geometer who commanded two thousand men","body":"During the First World War, Coolidge served as a major and liaison officer to the French General Staff, with two thousand American men under his command in Paris. France made him a chevalier of the Legion of Honor in 1919."},{"number":5,"category":"literature","header":"In retirement he wrote mathematics’ history","body":"After retiring in 1940, Coolidge turned to the history of his field, publishing studies of geometrical methods and \"The Mathematics of Great Amateurs.\" He was a record-setting miler in his Oxford days and a lifelong oarsman."}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6569","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1901,"children_ids":["HD6604","HD6605","HD6606","HD6607","HD6608"]}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD1263","link_text":"Prof. James Pelham Pierpont","display_label":"a fellow eminent American mathematics professor of the era"}],"slug":"j